===Etymology 1===
From {{etyl|enm}} {{term|feer|lang=enm}}, {{term|fere|lang=enm}}, {{term|fer|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|ang}} {{term|fær|fǣr|lang=ang}}, {{term|gefær|ġefǣr|calamity, sudden danger, peril, sudden attack, terrible sight|lang=ang}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{recons|fēran||danger|lang=gem-pro}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{recons|per-||to attempt, try, research, risk|lang=ine-pro}}. Cognate with {{etyl|nl|-}} {{term|gevaar||danger, risk, peril|lang=nl}}, {{etyl|de|-}} {{term|Gefahr||danger, risk, hazard|lang=de}}, {{etyl|sv|-}} {{term|fara||danger, risk, peril|lang=sv}}, {{etyl|la|-}} {{term|periculum|perīculum|danger, risk, trial|lang=la}}. Albanian {{term|frikë||fear,danger|lang=sq}} and Romanian {{term|frǐca||fear|lang=ro}} are also cognates, although probably influenced by an early Germanic variant.

====Noun====
{{en-noun|s|-}}

# {{uncountable}} A strong, uncontrollable, unpleasant [[emotion]] caused by actual or perceived danger or threat.
#: ''He was struck by '''fear''' on seeing the snake.''
# {{countable}} A [[phobia]], a sense of fear induced by something or someone.<!--not a self-referential definition: the word "fear" here is used in the previous sense-->
#: ''Not everybody has the same '''fears'''.''
#: ''I have a '''fear''' of [[ant]]s.''
# {{uncountable}} Extreme [[veneration]] or [[awe]], as toward a supreme being or deity.

